{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1fd0142e-e0b6-4563-8f5b-d59a06f32e4d","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` tells the page not to *inset* content for safe areas, but it doesn't make the app draw **behind** system bars. You need two more things:\n\n**1. Android — enable edge-to-edge mode** in `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    AndroidX.Activity.EdgeToEdge.Enable(this);\n}\n```\n\nThis makes your app draw behind the status bar and navigation bar (default on Android 15+, but required for earlier versions).\n\n**2. iOS — disable safe-area insets** on the page:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n**3. Make sure the Image actually fills the space:**\n\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       VerticalOptions=\"Fill\"\n       HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n```\n\nAlso verify the parent layout (e.g., `Grid`) has `Padding=\"0\"` and no `Margin` set.\n\n**TL;DR:** `SafeAreaEdges` controls content insets, but on Android you must explicitly opt into edge-to-edge rendering via `EdgeToEdge.Enable()`, and on iOS you need `UseSafeArea=\"False\"`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f18042a8-9b89-40bb-b6c8-598ba3cc4699","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI full-screen/edge-to-edge display. They want an image to go behind the status bar and navigation bar, and they've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but it's not working.\n\nThis is a knowledge question about .NET MAUI, not a codebase task. Let me answer from what I know.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve edge-to-edge content:\n\n1. `SafeAreaEdges` on `ContentPage` — this was introduced but might not be sufficient alone.\n2. You need to also handle platform-specific configurations.\n\n\n3. On Android, especially with Android 15 and later, edge-to-edge is the default behavior, but for earlier versions you need to explicitly opt in using `Window.DecorFitsSystemWindows = false` or the newer `EdgeToEdge` APIs.\n4. On iOS, you'll need to manage safe area insets properly to ensure content extends behind system UI elements.\n\nFor .NET 9 and beyond, MAUI introduced better support for edge-to-edge layouts through platform-specific properties like `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` and control-level properties that let you ignore safe areas when needed. The key is making sure your Image or content control has appropriate aspect settings and no padding that would prevent it from truly extending edge-to-edge. that property might exist in newer MAUI versions but isn't the complete solution. The real issue is that Android needs explicit edge-to-edge configuration—either through platform-specific APIs in MainActivity or newer Android 15+ defaults—and the image itself needs `AspectFill` to properly fill the space behind the system bars.\n\nWriting Android edge-to-edge setup... I need to focus on the Android implementation details to actually solve this problem.","outputTokens":1705,"requestId":"0442:FA277:130E04B:1569A99:6A027C68"},"id":"5724b135-e5b7-4498-9f8f-3427f4262e59","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:04:11.871Z","parentId":"b9f2ddf6-1451-458c-871e-4a85699d6fab"}
